If signal them that the cobblestone were solved, it would not be no more necessary to repair 200 about a thousand blackcurrants every season of rain in the Metropolitan Zone of Valle of México, warns Rafael Herrera Nájera, researcher of the Faculty of Chemistry (FQ) of the UNAM, who has assured that if the process of building and maintenance of the bituminous cobblestone is appropriate, the blackcurrants could be reduced or even eliminated completely.
During his conference A technological opinion about the blackcurrants, organized within the framework of the International Year of the Chemistry, it has announced that the laboratory of which it is responsible develops asphalts modified with polymers to cause a mixture having similar characteristics to those of the asphalt, but with a greater mechanical resistance, so much to high as low temperatures.
Herrera Nájera has considered that this type of modified asphalts could be used in places in which the climate is heat, as some cities of the north of the country, extremely to improve the yield, and consequently, the training of the blackcurrants.
It has explained that the asphalt, the heavier part of the oil, is a unity of molecules of hydrocarbons, of the molecules with a heavier molecular weight, called asphaltènes, and of the molecules with a low molecular weight, called malthènes, that unity give to the cobblestone her characteristic behavior viscoélastique.
The viscoélastique behavior of the asphalt consists in the fact that at high temperatures, of nearly 180 degrees, comprises as a liquid, at 120 degrees C his viscosity is very big and at 50 degrees C it presents a nearly solid state, while at very low temperatures, the asphalt becomes brittle, it added.
That means that in the streets the resistance of the asphalt is not regular and is altered for the day according to the environmental conditions and of temperature, warns the specialist in chemical engineering.
The researcher of the FQ has observed that the streets of Ciudad of México in their majority were covered by a flexible cobblestone, compound of six coats of materials, the three last ones of which imply the asphalt.
Between the more superficial coats finds itself the coat of asphalt, formed by small stones soaked in asphalt and compacted ulteriorly.
Each of the small stones that forms the coat, it signaled, is bathed year asphalt.
While the vehicles pass generating efforts, this lets the strengths spread very well in the cobblestone.
If one had modified asphalt, these would spread better, had an opinion to strive it chemical.
On the coat of asphalt, it says, one puts a last coat called coat of rotation, made in thin stone, in other words, of the sand that is also soaked in asphalt.
As this is the coat in contact with the wheels of the vehicles, it must have more de force mechanics than the coat of asphalt and supply adherence in the street.
Being the part of the cobblestone that receives and distribute the efforts, the coat of rotation also requires that this has an appropriate thickness and the material of which it is made must be looked.
The climate, especially the dampness and the variations of temperature, are also a very important factor to consider, especially the water, it says, because these affect considerably the yield of the coat of asphalt.
While the ground wets itself, the water spreads inside the coat is it is difficult that this goes out, it that soft all the coats of the cobblestone and consequently cause of the blackcurrants.
In the trial of training of a blackcurrant, it says, the first who is wasted is the film of rotation and only ulteriorly is affected the coat of asphalt, but the shame does not take place immediately, but it is a process that must be cured to the first signals with appropriate programs of maintenance.
The member of the National System of the Researchers has explained that the load of vehicles is another important factor for the training of blackcurrant and consequently the thickness of every coat of the cobblestone must always be bound pending vehicles and to guarantee his satisfaction, to avoid the frequent training of blackcurrant.
Rafael Herrera has warned of it being still a lot to investigate and to work the bituminous emulsions on the asphalt, for example, which in other countries exist already on the market and allow repairing the blackcurrants easily and without having to use high temperatures.
